# Production Readiness Rule

Treat all code as production code. Do not write demo-only code.

Avoid:
- hardcoded mock data unless explicitly requested
- fake auth checks
- console.log debugging left in code
- silent catch blocks
- broad `any` types
- unvalidated inputs
- client-side-only security checks
- unhandled promise rejections
- optimistic success messages before confirmation

Use real validation, real errors, and clear fallback behaviour.

Security:
- validate user input on the server
- enforce authorization server-side
- never expose secrets, service-role keys, or tokens in frontend code
- do not leak internal errors or sensitive data to users or logs
- do not bypass RLS with client-side logic

UI: keep layouts simple and purposeful. Every element needs a clear user purpose. Include loading, empty, and error states. No fake metrics, placeholder dashboards, or decorative bloat.
